<p>The <code>url</code> function URL-encodes a string for use in URLs.</p>

<h2>Basic Usage</h2>
<pre>{open}echo $urlText | url{close}</pre>
<p>Result: <b>{echo $urlText | url}</b></p>

<h2>Spaces and Special Chars</h2>
<pre>{open}echo 'hello world' | url{close}</pre>
<p>Encoded: <b>{echo 'hello world' | url}</b></p>

<h2>Query Parameter</h2>
<pre>{open}echo 'search term & more' | url{close}</pre>
<p>Safe for URL: <b>{echo 'search term & more' | url}</b></p>

<h2>Chained Examples</h2>
<pre>{open}echo 'My Document.pdf' | url{close}</pre>
<p>Filename: <b>{echo 'My Document.pdf' | url}</b></p>

<pre>{open}echo $sampleText | left(10) | url{close}</pre>
<p>Partial encoded: <b>{echo $sampleText | left(10) | url}</b></p>

<h2>Building URLs</h2>
<pre>?search={open}echo 'hello world' | url{close}</pre>
<p>Result: <b>?search={echo 'hello world' | url}</b></p>

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>Use this when building query strings or encoding values for URLs.</p>
